            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "for future reference, it's helpful to un-backtick SHAs and issue numbers so they are hyperlinked.\r\n\r\nit's good that this adds a test, that at least gives us something to work with while we find a simpler solution. though the test itself looks like it may be testing a specific solution rather than simulating the actual attack?\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n> Today `buf_write_make_backup()` removes the backup pathname and recreates it with `os_copy()`. That means the backup path is reopened by name after the unlink, so an attacker can replace it with a symlink in between. If `:write` later needs to restore from that backup, the restore path also trusts the pathname and can overwrite another file.\r\n\r\nIsn't there a simpler way to guard against this? Maybe check inode, or hash the contents. Anything but the current jumble of changes here ... :)\r\n\r\nthe reliance on \"already-open fds\" seems fragile. \r\n\r\nedit: suggestion by claude:\r\n\r\n> the simpler defense is to never reopen by name at all: use O_NOFOLLOW when creating the backup (fails if the path is a symlink), or create with O_EXCL (fails if the path already exists, so the race window after unlink is caught).\r\n>\r\n>  Either of those is a one-line fix compared to the PR's fd-passing approach.",
