            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "> for future reference, it's helpful to un-backtick SHAs and issue numbers so they are hyperlinked.\r\n\r\nTIL\r\n\r\n1. First test revised to be less implementation-base\r\n\r\n2. A creation-only `O_NOFOLLOW` / `O_EXCL` change does not seem sufficient. In master, `buf_write_make_backup()` still removes and recreates the backup by pathname, then mutates it again by pathname in the same flow ([creation path](https://github.com/neovim/neovim/blob/8308544fe588f34f5e1985d1fb37f64b41f91873/src/nvim/bufwrite.c#L851-L883)). The backup pathname is then still trusted again in the [open-failure restore](https://github.com/neovim/neovim/blob/8308544fe588f34f5e1985d1fb37f64b41f91873/src/nvim/bufwrite.c#L1360-L1375), [conversion-failure restore](https://github.com/neovim/neovim/blob/8308544fe588f34f5e1985d1fb37f64b41f91873/src/nvim/bufwrite.c#L1650-L1657), and [patchmode](https://github.com/neovim/neovim/blob/8308544fe588f34f5e1985d1fb37f64b41f91873/src/nvim/bufwrite.c#L1745-L1752) paths.\r\n\r\n\r\n3. I took the inode point in the place where it actually closes the later trust issue: after creation, the patch records the created backup FileID, and later restore/patchmode only reuse the pathname if it still refers to that same file.\r\n\r\n\r\n4. The fd-based part is basically putting us back on the og vim model moreso than \"implementing a jumble of changes\" if you compare to the vim source. Namely, current Vim still creates `backupcopy` backups with `O_EXCL|O_NOFOLLOW` and copies through already-open fds in the same code path, with the code explicitly calling out a “symlink hacker attack?” there ([Vim current master](https://github.com/vim/vim/blob/036e40e6d80b1d71e57d3715ae20175ce09d7b78/src/bufwrite.c#L1448-L1516)).\r\n\r\nlastly, this patch already came out of heavy AI-assisted exploration, so I do not want to resolve the remaining design questions by layering on more AI suggestions but rather humans that know the write path way better than me (xd)\r\n\r\n",
